-size:
this function is used to return the number of elements in the container.

example:

---------------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::deque<int> myDeque;

    // Adding elements
    myDeque.push_back(10);
    myDeque.push_back(20);
    myDeque.push_back(30);

    // Printing the number of elements
    std::cout << myDeque.size();

    return 0;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------

-empty:
this function is used to check if the container is empty.

if the container has no elements, it returns true.
otherwise, it returns false.

example:

---------------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::deque<int> myDeque;

    // Checking if the deque is empty
    if (myDeque.empty()) {
        std::cout << "The deque is empty";
    } else {
        std::cout << "The deque is not empty";
    }

    return 0;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------

-front:
this function is used to access the first element of the deque.

it does not remove the element.
it only returns the element at the front.

example:

---------------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::deque<int> myDeque;

    // Adding elements
    myDeque.push_back(10);
    myDeque.push_back(20);
    myDeque.push_back(30);

    // Accessing the first element
    std::cout << myDeque.front();

    return 0;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------

-back:
this function is used to access the last element of the deque.

it does not remove the element.
it only returns the element at the back.

example:

---------------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::deque<int> myDeque;

    // Adding elements
    myDeque.push_back(10);
    myDeque.push_back(20);
    myDeque.push_back(30);

    // Accessing the last element
    std::cout << myDeque.back();

    return 0;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------

-clear:
this function is used to remove all elements from the deque.

after using this function, the deque becomes empty.

example:

---------------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::deque<int> myDeque;

    // Adding elements
    myDeque.push_back(10);
    myDeque.push_back(20);
    myDeque.push_back(30);

    // Removing all elements
    myDeque.clear();

    // Printing the number of elements
    std::cout << myDeque.size();

    return 0;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------

-note:

push_front()  -> adds an element at the beginning.
push_back()   -> adds an element at the end.

pop_front()   -> removes the first element.
pop_back()    -> removes the last element.

front()       -> accesses the first element.
back()        -> accesses the last element.

size()        -> returns how many elements exist.
empty()       -> checks whether the container has elements.
clear()       -> removes all elements.
